<br>
Narril, you said &quot; I know this may sound weird but in raid a guild if you are online it is assumed you will join the raid. By going /a it helps the raid leader know you aren't coming and they can form groups and plan accordingly.&quot;<br>
<br>
Firstly, you seem to be addressing this comment to Maravana.  As she's an officer in a raid guild, it seems rather presumptuous of you to tell her how a raid guild, or a guild raid for that matter, is run.  I think she has some idea.<br>
<br>
Secondly, you're wrong, which is to say that your generalization is not universally true.  The command <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> /who all GUILD</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> only shows the first 25 &quot;hits,&quot; so it's not at all reliable for a large raid.  It won't show people who are zoning.  It won't show people who are linkdead.  Sure, you can get a full list of all guildmembers in the zone, but if you're not raiding, what are you doing in the zone?  And in any case, anon members still show within the zone in such a listing.<br>
<br>
My guild, which I believe could reasonably be termed a raid guild, has developed an extremely effective method for handling raid attendance.  A &quot;groups&quot; person is announced.  It is each member's responsibility to report to the groups person via tell.  If you don't report for duty, you don't get a group.  Simple and devastatingly effective.<br>
<br>
Don't assume that because *you* handle raids in a certain way, that's the universal or the best way. <p><TABLE ALIGN="left" width="25%">
